== Clinical Importance

=== Inguinal Hernia

- Direct Inguinal Hernia  
- Indirect hernia runs through inguinal canal

=== Inguinal Canal Boundary

- *Anterior:*  
  Skin, Subcutaneous tissue, External oblique aponeurosis throughout whole length  
- *Posterior:*  
  Peritoneum, Fat pad, Transversalis fascia throughout whole length, medial 2/3 internal oblique aponeurosis  
- *Roof:*  
  Conjoint tendon  
- *Floor:*  
  Concave margin of inguinal ligament  

*Conjoint tendon:* Combined fiber of internal oblique aponeurosis and transversalis fascia.

Posterior wall → Direct hernia  
Deep ring → Indirect inguinal hernia

